First, we focused on the Cu/ITO side under different source-drain bias voltages (VDS) (Fig. 2e (i)–(v)). The negative slope of the potential near the Cu/ITO interface decreased with increasing VDS and became almost flat at 120 mV, indicating that ΦB at the Cu/ITO side was approximately 120 meV (Fig. 2h). Then, the slope changed from positive to negative slope at approximately 20 mV at the Ni/ITO side (Fig. 2f (i)–(v)), indicating that ΦB on the Ni/ITO side was approximately 20 meV (Fig. 2i). Using the SPCM method, different types of Mx/ITO devices were systematically measured, and each ΦB was carefully estimated from the VDS dependency of the SPCM (Table S3). The correlation between ΦB and the WF for different Mx/ITO interfaces is displayed in Fig. 3a. Several sets of devices tested and error bars are added (Fig. S1). It was found that all the data points except those for Ni followed a linear tendency in that ΦB was proportional to the WF following the equation ΦB\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
